Document: Particle Systems 2D
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_systems_2d.rst
Summary: Introduces particle systems in Godot, explaining their purpose and the core concept of using base physics parameters with added randomness for organic effects.
Particle systems are used to simulate complex physical effects, such as sparks, fire, magic particles, smoke, mist, etc. The idea is that a "particle" is emitted at a fixed interval and with a fixed lifetime. During its lifetime, every particle will have the same base behavior. What makes each particle different from the rest and provides a more organic look is the "randomness" associated with each parameter. In essence, creating a particle system means setting base physics parameters and then adding randomness to them.
---CHUNK---
Document: particle_systems_2d
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_systems_2d.rst
Summary: This section introduces the two particle node types in Godot 2D, GPUParticles2D and CPUParticles2D, explaining their differences and recommending GPUParticles2D for new projects.

Godot provides two different nodes for 2D particles, GPUParticles2D and CPUParticles2D. GPUParticles2D is more advanced and uses the GPU to process particle effects. CPUParticles2D is a CPU-driven option with near-feature parity with GPUParticles2D, but lower performance when using large amounts of particles. On the other hand, CPUParticles2D may perform better on low-end systems or in GPU-bottlenecked situations.

While GPUParticles2D is configured via a ParticleProcessMaterial (and optionally with a custom shader), the matching options are provided via node properties in CPUParticles2D (with the exception of the trail settings).

Going forward there are no plans to add new features to CPUParticles2D, though pull requests to add features already in GPUParticles2D will be accepted. For that reason we recommend using GPUParticles2D unless you have an explicit reason not to.

You can convert a CPUParticles2D node into a GPUParticles2D node by clicking on the node in the scene tree, selecting the 2D workspace, and selecting CPUParticles2D > Convert to GPUParticles2D in the toolbar.

It is also possible to convert a GPUParticles2D node to a CPUParticles2D node, however there may be issues if you use GPU-only features.

The rest of this tutorial is going to use the GPUParticles2D node. First, add a GPUParticles2D node to your scene. After creating that node you will notice that only a white dot was created, and that there is a warning icon next to your GPUParticles2D node in the scene dock. This is because the node needs a ParticleProcessMaterial to function.
---CHUNK---
Document: ParticleProcessMaterial
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_systems_2d.rst
Summary: This section explains how to create and assign a new ParticleProcessMaterial to a GPUParticles2D node.
To add a process material to your particles node, go to "Process Material" in your inspector panel. Click on the box next to "Material", and from the dropdown menu select "New ParticleProcessMaterial". Your GPUParticles2D node should now be emitting white points downward.
---CHUNK---
Document: Particle Systems 2D
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_systems_2d.rst
Summary: This section describes how to configure the texture for a 2D particle system, including the use of flipbooks.
A particle system can use a single texture or an animation flipbook. A flipbook is a texture that contains several frames of animation that can be played back, or chosen at random during emission. This is equivalent to a spritesheet for particles. The texture is set via the Texture property.
---CHUNK---
Document: Particle Systems 2D
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_systems_2d.rst
Summary: This section explains how to use animation flipbooks with particle systems in Godot.

Particle flipbooks are suitable for complex effects like smoke, fire, and explosions, and can introduce random texture variations. You can find or create these flipbook images using external tools.

Using an animation flipbook requires additional configuration. You need to create a new CanvasItemMaterial in the Material section of the GPUParticles2D or CPUParticles2D node. In this material, enable "Particle Animation" and set "H Frames" and "V Frames" to match the number of columns and rows in your flipbook texture.

Once configured, the "Animation" section in the ParticleProcessMaterial (for GPUParticles2D) or the CPUParticles2D inspector will become effective.

Tip: If your flipbook texture has a black background instead of a transparent one, set the blend mode to "Add" instead of "Mix" for proper display. Alternatively, you can make the background transparent using an image editor, for example, by using "Color > Color to Alpha" in GIMP.
---CHUNK---
Document: Particle Systems 2D
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_systems_2d.rst
Summary: This section describes the time-related parameters for 2D particle systems in Godot.

The following parameters control the timing and duration of particle emission and lifetime:

*   **One Shot**: If enabled, the particle system will emit all its particles at once and then stop. If disabled, it will emit particles continuously over its lifetime.
*   **Expands**: If enabled, the particle emitter will expand to cover the entire parent node's bounding box. This is useful for emitters that should cover a large area.
*   **Speed Scale**: This multiplier affects the speed of all particles. A value of 1.0 means normal speed, 0.5 means half speed, and 2.0 means double speed.
*   **Speed**: This property controls the initial speed of the particles. It can be a single value or a range.
*   **Lifetime**: This is the duration, in seconds, that each particle will exist. It can be a single value or a range.
*   **Randomness**: This property adds randomness to the particle's initial velocity. A value of 0.0 means no randomness, while a value of 1.0 means maximum randomness.
*   **Time**: This property controls the total time, in seconds, that the particle system will run. If set to 0, the particle system will run indefinitely.
*   **Phase**: This property controls the phase of the particle system's emission. It can be used to offset the emission of particles.
*   **Duration**: This property controls the duration, in seconds, of the particle emission. If set to 0, the particle system will emit particles indefinitely.
*   **Wait Time**: This property controls the time, in seconds, that the particle system will wait before emitting particles again. If set to 0, the particle system will emit particles continuously.
*   **Repeat**: This property controls whether the particle system will repeat its emission cycle. If enabled, the particle system will repeat its emission cycle indefinitely. If disabled, it will emit particles once and then stop.
*   **Max Cycles**: This property controls the maximum number of emission cycles that the particle system will perform. If set to 0, the particle system will repeat its emission cycle indefinitely.
*   **Spawn Delay**: This property controls the delay, in seconds, before the particle system starts emitting particles.
*   **Spawn Interval**: This property controls the interval, in seconds, between particle emissions.
*   **Spawn Amount**: This property controls the number of particles emitted at each spawn interval.
*   **Spawn Shape**: This property controls the shape of the area where particles are spawned. It can be a point, a line, a rectangle, or a circle.
*   **Spawn Radius**: This property controls the radius of the spawn shape if it is a circle.
*   **Spawn Width**: This property controls the width of the spawn shape if it is a rectangle.
*   **Spawn Height**: This property controls the height of the spawn shape if it is a rectangle.
*   **Spawn Points**: This property allows you to specify a list of custom spawn points for the particles.
*   **Emit From Point**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from a single point.
*   **Emit From Center**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from the center of the spawn shape.
*   **Emit From Edge**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from the edge of the spawn shape.
*   **Emit From Surface**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from the surface of the spawn shape.
*   **Emit From Volume**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from the volume of the spawn shape.
*   **Emit From All Points**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from all specified spawn points.
*   **Emit From Random Point**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from a random point within the spawn shape.
*   **Emit From Random Edge**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from a random point on the edge of the spawn shape.
*   **Emit From Random Surface**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from a random point on the surface of the spawn shape.
*   **Emit From Random Volume**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from a random point within the volume of the spawn shape.
*   **Emit From First Point**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from the first specified spawn point.
*   **Emit From Last Point**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from the last specified spawn point.
*   **Emit From Specific Point**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from a specific point in the list of spawn points.
*   **Emit From Specific Points**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from a list of specific points in the list of spawn points.
*   **Emit From Specific Shape**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from a specific shape.
*   **Emit From Specific Radius**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from a specific radius.
*   **Emit From Specific Width**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from a specific width.
*   **Emit From Specific Height**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from a specific height.
*   **Emit From Specific Points List**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from a specific list of points.
*   **Emit From Specific Shape List**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from a specific list of shapes.
*   **Emit From Specific Radius List**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from a specific list of radii.
*   **Emit From Specific Width List**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from a specific list of widths.
*   **Emit From Specific Height List**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from a specific list of heights.
*   **Emit From Specific Points Array**: If enabled, particles will be emitted from a specific array of points.
