Document: Particle Systems 2D
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_systems_2d.rst
Summary: Describes the "One Shot" property of GPUParticles2D nodes.
One Shot
When enabled, a GPUParticles2D node will emit all of its particles once and then never again.
---CHUNK---
Document: Particle Systems 2D
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_systems_2d.rst
Summary: Controls the initial processing time of a 2D particle system.
Preprocess: This property controls the initial processing time of a 2D particle system. When set, the particle system will simulate a given number of seconds before it is actually drawn for the first time. This prevents particle systems like torches or mist from emitting particles immediately upon scene loading, providing a smoother visual transition.
---CHUNK---
Document: Particle Systems 2D
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_systems_2d.rst
Summary: Explains the Speed Scale property of 2D particle systems.
Speed Scale
The speed scale has a default value of 1 and is used to adjust the speed of a particle system. Lowering the value will make the particles slower while increasing the value will make the particles much faster.
---CHUNK---
Document: Particle Systems 2D
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_systems_2d.rst
Summary: Explains the explosiveness parameter in 2D particle systems.
Explosiveness controls how particles are emitted over their lifetime.
- 0: Particles are emitted at regular intervals. This is the default behavior.
- 1: All particles are emitted simultaneously at the start.
Values between 0 and 1 provide a blend between these two behaviors. This parameter is useful for creating effects like explosions or sudden bursts of particles.
---CHUNK---
Document: Particle Systems 2D
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_systems_2d.rst
Summary: Explains how randomness is applied to particle system physics parameters.
Randomness
All physics parameters can be randomized. Random values range from 0 to 1. The formula to randomize a parameter is:
initial_value = param_value + param_value * randomness
---CHUNK---
Document: Particle Systems 2D
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_systems_2d.rst
Summary: Explains the Fixed FPS setting for 2D particle systems and a workaround for physics interpolation issues.
Fixed FPS
This setting can be used to set the particle system to render at a fixed FPS. For instance, changing the value to 2 will make the particles render at 2 frames per second. Note this does not slow down the particle system itself.
Note: Godot 4.3 does not currently support physics interpolation for 2D particles. As a workaround, disable physics interpolation for the particles node by setting Node > Physics Interpolation > Mode at the bottom of the inspector.
---CHUNK---
Document: Particle Systems 2D
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_systems_2d.rst
Summary: Explains the effect of the "Fract Delta" setting on particle systems.
Setting Fract Delta to true results in fractional delta calculation, which has a smoother particles display effect. This increased smoothness stems from higher accuracy. The difference is more noticeable in systems with high randomness or fast-moving particles. It helps maintain the visual consistency of the particle system, making sure that each particle's motion aligns with its actual lifespan. Without it, particles might appear to jump or move more than they should in a single frame if they are emitted at a point within the frame. The greater accuracy has a performance tradeoff, particularly in systems with a higher amount of particles.
---CHUNK---
Document: Particle Systems 2D
Path: godot/tutorials/2d/particle_systems_2d.rst
Summary: This section describes the drawing parameters for 2D particle systems in Godot.

The drawing parameters control how particles are rendered.

**Visibility**

*   **Visible on screen**: If enabled, the particle system will only be drawn when it is within the screen bounds. This can improve performance by not rendering particles that are off-screen.

**Rendering**

*   **Texture**: The texture to be used for rendering the particles. If not set, particles will not be rendered.
*   **Region**: If enabled, only a portion of the texture will be used. This is useful for sprite sheets.
    *   **Region Rect**: Defines the rectangular area of the texture to be used.
*   **Modulate**: A color multiplier applied to the particle's color. This allows for tinting the particles.
*   **Shading**: Controls how the particle's color interacts with the light.
    *   **Light Shader**: The shader to use for lighting.
*   **Transparency**: Controls how transparent the particles are.
    *   **Alpha Cut**: The threshold for alpha cutoff. Pixels below this threshold will be discarded.
    *   **Blend Mode**: The blending mode used for transparency. Options include "Mix", "Add", "Sub", and "Mul".
*   **Cull Mode**: Determines how backfaces are culled. Options include "Disabled", "Front", and "Back".
*   **Flip H**: Flips the texture horizontally.
*   **Flip V**: Flips the texture vertically.
*   **Z Sort**: If enabled, particles will be sorted by their Z-depth. This is useful for ensuring correct rendering order when particles overlap.
*   **Fixed Size**: If enabled, particles will maintain their size regardless of distance from the camera.
*   **Use Invert**: If enabled, the texture will be inverted.
*   **Use Particle Color**: If enabled, the particle's color will be used to modulate the texture.
*   **Use Texture Color**: If enabled, the texture's color will be used to modulate the particle's color.
*   **Use Texture Alpha**: If enabled, the texture's alpha channel will be used to modulate the particle's alpha.
*   **Use Texture Normal Map**: If enabled, a normal map will be used for lighting.
*   **Use Texture Roughness Map**: If enabled, a roughness map will be used for lighting.
*   **Use Texture Metallic Map**: If enabled, a metallic map will be used for lighting.
*   **Use Texture Emission Map**: If enabled, an emission map will be used for lighting.
*   **Use Texture AO Map**: If enabled, an ambient occlusion map will be used for lighting.
*   **Use Texture Height Map**: If enabled, a height map will be used for displacement.
*   **Use Texture Normal Map Blend**: If enabled, the normal map will be blended with the base texture.
*   **Use Texture Roughness Map Blend**: If enabled, the roughness map will be blended with the base texture.
*   **Use Texture Metallic Map Blend**: If enabled, the metallic map will be blended with the base texture.
*   **Use Texture Emission Map Blend**: If enabled, the emission map will be blended with the base texture.
*   **Use Texture AO Map Blend**: If enabled, the ambient occlusion map will be blended with the base texture.
*   **Use Texture Height Map Blend**: If enabled, the height map will be blended with the base texture.
*   **Use Texture Normal Map Intensity**: Controls the intensity of the normal map.
*   **Use Texture Roughness Map Intensity**: Controls the intensity of the roughness map.
*   **Use Texture Metallic Map Intensity**: Controls the intensity of the metallic map.
*   **Use Texture Emission Map Intensity**: Controls the intensity of the emission map.
*   **Use Texture AO Map Intensity**: Controls the intensity of the ambient occlusion map.
*   **Use Texture Height Map Intensity**: Controls the intensity of the height map.
